properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Warm, windy, and rainy conditions are expected for the southwest Yukon and northwestern B.C. tonight and Wednesday. Areas exposed to winds from the southeast could see gusts to 60 km/h tonight and Wednesday as a powerful storm remains over the Gulf of Alaska. These strong winds will maintain the gradual warm up through Wednesday. Snow will change to rain later this evening as temperatures rise above freezing. Periods of rain are expected to continue through Wednesday with the potential for some areas to see 10 to 30 mm through Wednesday afternoon. These temperatures are 10 to 20 degrees Celsius above seasonal normals for this time of year. More seasonal conditions will return on Thursday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall continues tonight. Snow, heavy at times, and blowing snow will continue tonight. Additional snowfall amounts of 10 to 15 centimetres are possible before the snow weakens Wednesday morning. Falling snow, along with wind gusts up to 70 km/h, will allow for blowing snow to occur and significantly affect visibilities tonight and early Wednesday morning. This snowfall is the result of a low pressure system that has moved into southern Quebec this evening. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
